            <fr:title text="Stuff, Structure, and Properties">Stuff, Structure, and Properties</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>remark</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>When we define a <fr:link href="/gr-000G/" title="Group" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-000G/" display-uri="gr-000G" type="local">Group</fr:link> (or <fr:link href="/vectsp-0001/" title="Vector Space" uri="http://localhost:8000/vectsp-0001/" display-uri="vectsp-0001" type="local">Vector Space</fr:link> or...), we typically have a kind of "template" for the definition which looks like:</html:p>
  <html:blockquote><html:p>A <html:dfn>Gadget</html:dfn> consists of some <html:strong>stuff</html:strong> (sets or other gadgets like fields) equipped with some <html:strong>structure</html:strong> (functions, subsets, subset families like topologies, or specific elements) such that a bunch of <html:strong>properties</html:strong> (usually equations) hold.</html:p></html:blockquote>
<html:p>John Baez and James Dolan were the first to explore this template for definitions. See also Sections 2.4 and 3.1 of <fr:link href="/baez-2006-lectures/" title="Lectures on n-Categories and Cohomology" uri="http://localhost:8000/baez-2006-lectures/" display-uri="baez-2006-lectures" type="local">Baez and Shulman</fr:link>.</html:p><html:p>Model theorists typically describe this as a tuple (all the "stuff" and "structure" are crammed together into one tuple) which satisfy some axioms (the "properties"). While this is neat, it lacks some of the desired "inheritance" (like a <fr:link href="/field-0001/" title="Field" uri="http://localhost:8000/field-0001/" display-uri="field-0001" type="local">Field</fr:link> <html:em>really is</html:em> an Abelian group with addition, extended with a multiplication operator and a "one" element). Computer Scientists would suggest using a "finite map" instead of a tuple.</html:p><html:p>There is also some tension between "Mathematical Practice" and what is desirable when formalizing concepts in a proof assistant. For example, we would often want to define a group as a group object internal to the category of sets, but that adds a lot of needless complications to formalizing this in a proof assistant (where we would want as Spartan a structure as possible).</html:p></fr:mainmatter>
